06481nam a22009495i 9783110723977DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021935841  a97831107239777 a10.1515/97831107239772doi  a(DE-B1597)571295  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090102bisacsh00aPostcolonial Language Varieties in the Americas /ced. by Danae Maria Perez, Eeva Sippola. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKoloniale und Postkoloniale Linguistik / Colonial and Postcolonial Linguistics (KPL/CPL) ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tColonialism and new language varieties in the Americas: An introduction -- tPero – Champion of Hispanization? -- tA Mesoamerican perspective on contactinduced change in numeral classification -- tSecondary derivation in the Michif verb: Beyond the traditional Algonquian template -- tSocial conditioning for the transmission of adstrate features in contact varieties of Spanish in the Central Andes -- tThe Afro-Brazilian community Kalunga: Linguistic and sociohistorical perspectives -- tHispanicization in the Welsh settlement of Chubut Province, Argentina -- tComplex patterns of variety perception in the Eastern Caribbean -- tThe contested role of colonial language ideologies in multilingual Belize -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Languages -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Americas, both indigenous and postcolonial languages today bear witness of massive changes that have taken place since the colonial era. However, a unified approach to languages from different colonial areas is still missing.The present volume studies postcolonial varieties that emerged due to changing linguistic and sociolinguistic conditions in different settings across the Americas. The studies cover indigenous languages that are undergoing lexical and grammatical change due to the presence of colonial languages and the emergence of new dialects and creoles due to contact. The contributions showcase the diversity of approaches to tackle fundamental questions regarding the processes triggered by language contact as well as the wide range of outcomes contact has had in postcolonial settings.The volume adds to the documentation of the linguistic properties of postcolonial language varieties in a socio-historically informed framework. It explores the complex dynamics of extra-linguistic factors that brought about the processes of language change in them and contributes to a better understanding of the determinant factors that lead to the emergence and evolution of such codes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh  aLanguage Change.  aLanguage Contact.  aLanguage Documentation.  aLanguage Vitality.1 aArbes, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraga Mattos, Ana Paulla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazzoli, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerez, Danae Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerez, Danae Maria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRees, Iwan Wyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobbers, Maja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmalz, Mirjam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Britta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSippola, Eeva, econtributor.4ctb4h